Good catch. No, the way I wrote it, the collection-level pre-request script would generate a new customerUniqueID before every request, which would break the COA flow.

You need:

Iteration 1
------------
CheckDevice      -> customerUniqueID = 1001
VerifyPhone      -> customerUniqueID = 1001
ConfirmPasscode  -> customerUniqueID = 1001
Iteration 2
------------
CheckDevice      -> customerUniqueID = 1002
VerifyPhone      -> customerUniqueID = 1002
ConfirmPasscode  -> customerUniqueID = 1002

NOT:

CheckDevice      -> 1001
VerifyPhone      -> 1002
ConfirmPasscode  -> 1003

That would fail because RemoteRest correlates the transaction using the same customer identifier.

Better approach

Generate the ID only once at the beginning of each collection run.

Option 1 (Recommended)

Put this only in the CheckDevice pre-request script:

const id =
    Date.now().toString() +
    "_" +
    Math.floor(Math.random() * 100000);
pm.environment.set("customerUniqueID", id);

Then:

CheckDevice
VerifyPhone
ConfirmPasscode
ValidateLink

all use:

"customerUniqueID": "{{customerUniqueID}}"

and share the same value.

When the Collection Runner starts the next iteration, CheckDevice generates a new ID and the entire flow uses that new ID.

⸻

Even better for debugging

Add this test script to CheckDevice:

console.log(
    "Iteration CustomerUniqueID:",
    pm.environment.get("customerUniqueID")
);

Now you can see exactly which transaction belongs to which iteration.

⸻

Another thing to verify

From the COA flow documents we reviewed months ago, some downstream requests may require values returned by previous responses.

Examples:

personId
verificationId
sessionId
passcodeId

If your VerifyPhone or ConfirmPasscode endpoints require one of those values, you’ll need to capture them from the previous response:

const response = pm.response.json();
pm.environment.set(
    "personId",
    response.personId
);

and then use:

{
  "personId": "{{personId}}"
}

in the next request.

Before building the automation, I would run:

CheckDevice
VerifyPhone
ConfirmPasscode

manually once and inspect:

* request body
* response body

to see what correlation fields are actually required besides customerUniqueID.

That will save you a lot of frustration when you automate 100 iterations.
